<font color="#FF0000">NURSE RATCHET</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 10  1:03:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It seems every protestor always say they were trying to end the war. As others have said, it ended after the politics of it came to an end. Even McNamara admitted &quot;quantitatively, we are winning...&quot;.<br><br>
That being as it may, if the protestors had given us respect when we returned, we would not hve the difficulty respecting them. We were abused in many ways when we got off the planes. When I was abused, I shut off the world and my first wife. It nearly destroyed me. 25 years later, I am still trying to get my life in order. Even the PTSD is a part of me.<br><br>
Arthur's question is a valid one. If there were no war in Vietnam, we may have gone to Nicuargua. Or maybe not. For me the Army was a way to get out of the ghetto and make something of myself.<br><br>
Unfortunately, I have been called a murderer, war-monger, puppet, etc. I was a soldier in a war we didnot have the resolve to end. That resolve was not known when Truman gave support to the French by the American people.<br><br>
None of that matters now. What matters is we have to set aside our anger towards each other or the &quot;communist's&quot; of the '70's have already destroyed this land. The generation we grew up in has turned from a self-indulgent group to a selfish group. Just look at our political reality in Washington now.
<p><code>-- ahernand@manc.edu  (Alex J Hernandez) </code><p>


